{% extends "_layouts/blog.jinja" %}

{% block page_content %}

<h3 id="intro">Intro</h3>
<p>
  A {{ text::emphasize(text="tuple") }}
 is 
  a sequence of values, which can be of different 
  types. 
  A tuple is defined with circle brackets 
  {{ text::emphasize(text="()") }}
.
</p>

{{ text::code_block(
  header="rust",
  language="rust",
  code=`// Create a tuple with 3 elements.
let stuff = ("stuff", 42, 'a');

// Annotate the types of the tuple values.
let things: (&str, u8, char) = ("things", 69, 'z');

// Tuple elements are accessed with the dot '(.)' operator 
// and their 'index' number.
println!("{}", stuff.0); // => stuff
println!("{}", things.1); // => 69

// All the elements of a tuple can be destructured into a pattern.
let (a, b, c) = stuff;`
) }}

<h3 id="considerations">Considerations</h3>
<ul>
  <li>The number of elements in a tuple is known as its {{ text::emphasize(text="arity") }}
.</li>
  <li>{{ text::emphasize(text="Traits") }}
 are only implemented on a {{ text::emphasize(text="tuple") }}
 with an {{ text::emphasize(text="arity") }}
 of {{ text::emphasize(text="12") }}
 or less.</li>
  <li>Tuples with an {{ text::emphasize(text="arity") }}
 greater than {{ text::emphasize(text="12") }}
 lose most of their functionality.</li>
</ul>

{% endblock page_content %}